I am honored to share I was invited by the Consulates of Mexico to participate in the third binational conference this weekend for Mexican origin artists now living in the US. 

It has been an incredible experience to meet so many talented artists, get to know the city that has an incredible art center and most important part to be somewhat of a representative of my adopted city of Houston in my own country of Mexico. 

We had art workshops, art talks, round tables about future opportunities in our relationship with the consulate and Mexico to promote our own art.

Today we will do some sightseeing including the border, the school of Fine Arts, & some government offices. This is a beginning of a new relationship that I hope to grow and bring my work to my homeland in the future. 👨🏻‍🎨🇲🇽🎨🖌

Special thanks to the @consulmexhouston for the invite!

Wrapping up 2022 with another year that I am incredibly thankful for. Looking back here are a few of my favorite memories that stood out:

👨🏻‍🎨 Started the year with moving into a studio 3x as big at Winter Street Studios!

📺 Made my love TV debut with Deborah Duncan and was featured on KHOU x Cadillac “Shaping Houston” segment. 

🇲🇽 Was invited by the Mexican Consulates to participate in the 3rd binational conference  for Mexican origin artists living in the US. 

🏡 Finally made a long overdue trip to my hometown where I was welcomed and interviewed by the local news.

✈️ Found new inspirations through travel to Europe where I visited Picasso & Van Gogh Museums, Gaudí’s Casa Battlo and Lisbon Contemporary Museum, and the Amsterdam Museum of Art. 

🖼️ Took my work on the road again with The Other Art Fair Dallas with a new collection From my LIVE series. 

🏳️‍🌈 Shared my pride with a feature by Vizzy for LGBTQ+ pride in the Houston Chronicle.

🎗Continued helping raise funds for great causes including Fresh Arts, Artcetera, Tahirih, and Pablo Foundation.

🎤 Connected more with my local community with an artist talk at Klein Cane High School, Architecture Center Houston & Splendora Elementary. 

I am always humbled by the continued support from my community, family, and friends. Looking forward to an amazing 2023 of new adventures, inspirations, and new works!

Edgar Medina’s LIVE series is rooted in his mantra to live in the moment. Inspired by images seen in urban cities and years of change, his use of mixed media creates a sense of years of life through multiple layers of color and texture. You can find mixed media elements in the series, including personal photography and vintage papers such as vintage piano player scrolls. The bold typography defines his intent, and through the work, you can find other words of wisdom to inspire a positive outlook on life.

social_posts.post_text:
Starting the year with a new adventure even with the hurdles with my studio. I am staying positive, I haven't been able to work from my studio cause of the smoke damage, but that didn't stop me. I grabbed all my paints, and the materials I need & decided to do another trip to my homeland to look for new places to get inspired for new works. And the best way to do it, it’s to embark on a journey to Bacalar, enjoy the town, talk to people, and document my journey with lots of pictures & videos of the beautiful 
Lagoon of Seven Colors, you can see seven shades of blue in the water. I took this picture that inspired me to create and do the live painting because you can appreciate the stromatolites on the edge of the lagoon as well as the 7 shades of blues. 
 After last night, I can say I am inspired to continue this journey of traveling & creating Art. It is so refreshing to see firsthand what nature has to offer, get to know people from around the world who appreciate my work & be able to paint in the sunset. 
👨🏻‍🎨🎨🖌️🌊🏖️

I live for creating Art and traveling to new places to inspire my works. I called this series “LIVE” inspired by my mantra “Live in the Moment” to remind myself to enjoy every moment despite the whirlwind going around me. 

Inspired by images seen in urban cities and years of change, I used mixed media (including personal photography and vintage papers such as vintage piano player scrolls) to create a sense of years of life through multiple layers of color and texture. 

The bold typography defines my intent, and through the work, you can find other hidden words of wisdom to inspire a positive outlook on life. We only live once and we bettered make the best of it. 👨🏻‍🎨

Color meanings are the associations between colors and emotions. Or how colors affect us in different situations.

 Colors also catch our attention and make us stop to admire the artwork on display. The vibrancy of the colors draws us in, and we often spend a few minutes admiring each piece. Studies have shown that seeing vibrant color combinations can even release endorphins in our brains.

🌟 Exciting Announcement! 🌟
 
Last year, I had the incredible opportunity to participate in an artist workshop in Tijuana, Mexico. The workshop opened my eyes to the immense talent and creativity of Mexican artists living right here in the USA. Inspired by this, I made the decision when asked to create solo show to instead curate a group exhibition to shine a spotlight on the remarkable Mexican artists and artists with Mexican roots living in Houston.
 
At first, I could only think of a handful of artists to include, but as I delved deeper into the artistic community, my list grew rapidly. I am thrilled to share that "Beyond the Stereotype" now features an amazing lineup of 18 exceptionally talented Houston artists!
 
I am deeply honored and overflowing with pride to have curated this exhibit. Through "Beyond the Stereotype," we aim to challenge conventional expectations and showcase the profound impact and accomplishments of the Mexican immigrant community in the arts here in Houston.
 
I warmly invite each one of you to explore the profound connection between heritage, culture, and artistic expressions by visiting our website below. You'll find an exquisite collection of artworks, each carrying a unique story and perspective.
 
If you prefer experiencing art firsthand, I have fantastic news! The show is open to the public, and admission is free. You can drop by the Consulate of Mexico, Monday to Friday, from 8 am to 4 pm. It's an opportunity you won't want to miss!
 
Let's celebrate the rich diversity of our artistic community and honor the contributions of Mexican artists in Houston. Together, let's go "Beyond the Stereotype"!

While preparing for the exhibit "Beyond the Stereotype," I embarked on a personal journey to create a painting that truly reflects my identity as an artist. Inspired by the vibrant colors of Mexico's streets and the abstract influences of living in the USA, I created "Intertwined" or "Entrelazados." This artwork is inspired by the beautiful and colorful fabrics created by the indigenous people of Mexico, symbolizing our interconnectedness in one way or another. It also represents & celebrates my accomplishments as a Mexican immigrant in this community, breaking through conventional expectations and leaving my mark with a diverse perspective through my Artwork and that embodies what the exhibit is about. 
I invite you to visit the exhibition and explore the profound connection between heritage, culture, and the artistic expressions of each participating artist. The exhibit is open to the public Monday to Friday, from 8:00 AM to 4:00 PM, at the Mexican Consulate in Houston.
